ed DNA viruses)","Togaviridae (single-stranded RNA viruses)","Poxviridae (large DNA viruses)"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERubella is a member of the \u003Cstrong\u003ETogaviridae\u003C/strong\u003E family. These viruses are characterised by:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESingle-stranded, positive-sense RNA genome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003ESpherical, enveloped virions 60-70nm in diameter\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncludes two genera: Alphavirus and Rubivirus\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe other virus families have different characteristics:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPapovaviridae\u003C/strong\u003E are non-enveloped DNA viruses that include papillomaviruses\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReoviridae\u003C/strong\u003E contain double-stranded RNA and cause gastroenteritis\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHepadnaviridae\u003C/strong\u003E include hepatitis B with partially double-stranded DNA\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoxviridae\u003C/strong\u003E are large, complex DNA viruses that replicate in the cytoplasm\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Rubella virus belongs to the Togaviridae family, which are single-stranded RNA viruses with an envelope","Togaviruses are transmitted by arthropods or respiratory routes and can cause significant human disease"],"references":["Sastry, A. S., \u0026 Bhat, S. (2018). Essentials of medical microbiology. JP Medical Ltd","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Pollard AJ, Bijker EM. A guide to vaccinology: from basic principles to new developments. Nat Rev Immunol. 2021 Feb;21(2):83-100. doi: 10.1038/s41577-020-00479-7. Epub 2020 Dec 22. Erratum in: Nat Rev Immunol. 2021 Feb;21(2):129. doi: 10.1038/s41577-020-00497-5. PMID: 33353987; PMCID: PMC7754704."]},"relat